<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-201-458  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 201 458.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  April 17 1989 v23 n16 p83(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>From the back room to the boardroom. (MIS)(John Donovan)(interview)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Crane, Katie.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>In an interview with John Donovan, professor of management atMassachusetts Institute of Technology's Sloan School ofManagement, he says that information system (IS) executives mustwork more successfully with business executives to ensure thevalue of the IS to the corporation.andP;  Donovan says that most MISmanagers make the mistake of attempting to design systems fromscratch, which wastes time and money, rather than building systemsthat fit into the company's business strategy.andP;  Donovan believesthat MIS executives must stop viewing themselves as technicalpersonnel and instead begin acting like strategic boardroomexecutives, thinking about the IS's return on investment.andP;  Donovanrecommends that CEOs create an education program for the ISexecutive that teaches how to identify strategic opportunities andwhat technologies should be implemented in strategic applications.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     InterviewMISChief Executive OfficersCooperationCompanies.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   John Donovan. (portrait)Person:    Donovan, John (attitudes).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>